  "final_analysis": "Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH) is a group of genetic conditions limiting hormone production in the adrenal glands. The most common form is due to 21-hydroxylase deficiency, which can lead to excess androgen production and virilization in a female fetus. The goal of prenatal treatment is to suppress fetal adrenal androgen production to prevent this virilization. Dexamethasone is the drug of choice because it can cross the placenta and effectively suppress fetal adrenal activity, reducing androgen production. This aligns with the consensus in medical literature that Dexamethasone is used for this specific purpose. Other corticosteroids like Betamethasone, Hydrocortisone, and Prednisolone do not have the same efficacy in crossing the placenta or suppressing fetal adrenal function for this indication.",
